### **üî∏ `doc_internal/` Rules**

This folder contains non-public artefacts (which should *not be re-sent to the LLM automatically* unless explicitly needed):

* **ARCHITECTURE.md** ‚Äî formal architecture document  
* **OPERATIONAL\_RULES.md** ‚Äî specific coding rules  
* **CONTEXT.md** ‚Äî summaries intended for Claude  
* **HISTORY.md** ‚Äî timestamped log of prior sessions  
* **CLAUDE.md** ‚Äî Claude Code manifest & default rules

This structure avoids accidental repetition of *full context* in prompts, saving tokens over time. ([YouTube](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=P-5bWpUbO60&utm_source=chatgpt.com))

## **üìú 3\. Model Selection & Prompt Modules**

Claude Code (Opus 4.5+) supports model selection and prompt scaffolding. Use **prompt modules** ‚Äî reusable sections ‚Äî and use *prompt caching* where supported:

\[MODEL CONFIG\]  
model: Opus 4.5  
effort: medium  
context\_chunk: doc\_internal/CONTEXT.md

\[PROMPT CACHE KEYS\]  
global\_rules  
design\_invariants  
shared\_architecture

**Effort Levels**

* *Low* ‚Äî exploratory research (cheap, less reasoning)  
* *Medium* ‚Äî design reasoning \+ nuanced tasks  
* *High* ‚Äî full architectural work, agentic execution

This lets you trade token cost vs reasoning depth. ([Wikipedia](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_%28language_model%29?utm_source=chatgpt.com))

## **üß† 4\. Universal Engineering Rules (Enforce Across Copilots)**

These should live in **OPERATIONAL\_RULES.md** and be enforced by Claude Code / your local Copilot workflows:

### **üîπ General Best Practices**

1. Follow **SOLID**, **Clean Architecture**, **Pragmatic Programmer** principles.  
2. Use **linting and formatting** (Prettier/ESLint for JS, Black/Flake8 for Python, Checkstyle/SonarLint for Java).  
3. No **hard-coded structured data** (JSON/XML inside code). Use config files.  
4. API design must be modular, testable, and versioned.  
5. Every production feature must have **automated tests** (unit \+ integration).

These rules should be *explicitly codified* and referenced by your agent workflows. ([YouTube](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=P-5bWpUbO60&utm_source=chatgpt.com))

### **üîπ CLI & Agent Safety Rules**

In `CLAUDE.md` or agent config:

RULE: ask\_before\_execute  
RULE: safety\_sanitize\_output  
RULE: no\_silent\_code\_changes

Meaning: never make silent changes; always request confirmation before edits, and sanitize outputs for security & compliance.

## **üì¶ 5\. Workflow Patterns (Consistent Across Sessions)**

**Planning phase** ‚Äî use **Opus** (or your highest-capability model) with **high effort**. This is where architectural mistakes happen, and they're expensive to fix later. You want Claude to think deeply about component boundaries, data models, API contracts, and auth flows. The token cost during planning is tiny compared to the cost of rebuilding after a bad architectural decision.

**Building phase** ‚Äî use **Sonnet** with **medium effort** for the bulk of implementation. Most implementation work (writing React components, API routes, Prisma models, tests) is well-defined once the plan exists. Sonnet handles this efficiently at lower cost and faster speed. Switch to Opus only when you hit something genuinely complex mid-build ‚Äî a tricky state machine, a concurrency issue, a subtle security concern.

**Quick tasks** (renaming, formatting, simple config changes, generating boilerplate) ‚Äî **Haiku** with **low effort**. Fast, cheap, good enough.

![][image1]

The principle is simple: **pay for intelligence where mistakes are costly, use speed where the path is clear.**

Below are **repeatable workflows** you can share across different Copilots and LLM models:

---

### **üõ†Ô∏è A) Research & Planning Workflow**

**Start with:**

@mode research  
@model Opus 4.5  
@effort medium

Then use a structured prompt template:

Task: Summarize current domain knowledge for PROJECT\_X.  
Input: document references, URLs, code repo path  
Constraints:  
\- Return structured topics  
\- Produce taxonomy of concepts  
\- Output as JSON with sections: summary, key entities, risks, unknowns

*Save the result into* `doc_internal/CONTEXT.md` for reference ‚Äî and avoid re-pasting long summaries. ([YouTube](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=amEUIuBKwvg&utm_source=chatgpt.com))

---

### **üßæ B) Incremental System Design Workflow**

**Prompt skeleton:**

Task: Generate draft architecture  
Input: design goals \+ constraints  
Output:  
\- 3 architectural options ranked  
\- tradeoffs  
\- risks & mitigation  
\- integration points

Store this as **ARCHITECTURE.md**. Use version tags (v0.1, v0.2) so Claude can reference instead of re-regenerating.

---

### **üß™ C) Code Generation/Execution Workflow**

Switch to:

@mode execution  
@model Opus 4.5  
@effort high

Use a **diff-only pattern**:

Before:  
\<existing files\>

Task: Make changes for feature X  
Response format: diff (unified), tests added, summary

By *only returning diffs*, you avoid large code rewrites and reduce token costs.

## **üí∞ 6\. Token Efficiency Practices**

üìå **Prompt Caching** ‚Äî cache static headers like System Prompt and Global Rules so they aren‚Äôt re-sent each time.  
üìå **Chunk context manually** ‚Äî load only relevant parts rather than whole ARCHITECTURE.md. ([YouTube](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=EssztxE9P28&utm_source=chatgpt.com))  
üìå **Compact context periodically** ‚Äî use built-in `/compact` or explicit summarization to reduce token window.  
üìå **Session per task** ‚Äî finish a task, flush the context before starting another to avoid uncontrolled growth. ([YouTube](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=EssztxE9P28&utm_source=chatgpt.com))

---

## **üß™ 7\. Test & Validation Integration**

Inject automated validation steps at key points:

Trigger: code\_write  
Follow-up: run linters \+ test suite  
Output: failures \+ suggested fixes

Claude Code‚Äôs agent frameworks increasingly support test runs and integrations (even GitHub Actions). ([YouTube](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=nItsfXwujjg&utm_source=chatgpt.com))

---

## **üìä 8\. Versioning & Shared Rules**

Together with **CLAUDE.md**, maintain:

* `COPILOT_RULES.md` ‚Äî shared conventions for Copilots  
* `AGENT_MANIFEST.md` ‚Äî mappings of agent behaviors (refactorer, architect, reviewer)  
* `DEPLOY_PIPELINE.md` ‚Äî CI/CD rules (SonarQube, code coverage)

This lets you treat Copilot/Claude workflows like real engineering assets ‚Äî *checked in, versioned, audited*.

Reflecting current research, ‚Äúagentic coding manifests‚Äù like Claude.md files play the same role as traditional build pipelines, and having well-structured manifests is critical in real development workflows. ([arXiv](https://arxiv.org/abs/2509.14744?utm_source=chatgpt.com))
